title: Chartway Credit Union <> Webstacks || Website Redesign & CMS Migration Proposal

textRun.content: Chartway Credit Union is embarking on a critical initiative to modernize its public-facing website and content management system. Webstacks will partner with Chartway Credit Union to redesign and redevelop
into a modern, mobile-first, member-centric digital experience.

The new site will reflect Chartway’s brand, serve its three distinct regional markets (Virginia, Utah, Texas) with geotargeted content, and support personalization, compliance, and future growth. We will implement an intuitive UX/UI that simplifies navigation and encourages exploration, driving lead generation through personalized content and guided user pathways. Key features will include dynamic, region-specific rates and content, multilingual support (English/Spanish), ADA-compliant design, and seamless integrations with Chartway’s marketing and banking systems (e.g. Marketo, online banking portals, MeridianLink/TCI loan applications, etc.).
built on a modern tech stack
(such as Sanity, Storyblok, or Contentful) for flexibility, a
front-end for performance, and hosting on

for scalability and speed. This composable architecture will ensure high performance (aiming for 90%+ site health and Core Web Vitals scores), security (SOC 2 compliance, TLS 1.2+, DDoS protection, MFA, and other best practices), and easy content management for Chartway’s team.
Our scope covers end-to-end redesign and migration. This includes:
Stakeholder workshops and discovery to align on goals
configured to support Chartway’s content models (marketing pages, blog posts, calculators, branch/ATM locator, etc.)
Front-end development of the site using Next.js (ensuring fully responsive and mobile-first layouts)
Integration of third-party tools (Marketo forms, online banking SSO, secure chat, calculators, etc.)
Thorough QA/testing (including accessibility audits to WCAG 2.1 AA standards)
Content migration and 301 redirect mapping from the current site to preserve SEO
Training of Chartway’s staff on the new CMS

All “must-have” requirements from the RFP will be addressed, including personalized content by user type and location, interactive tools (calculators, etc.) with intelligent search and locator features, ability to create campaign landing pages and vanity URLs, scheduled content publishing, role-based workflows for compliance approvals, and more. Post-launch, we will provide a support period to ensure a smooth transition.
We have mapped out a timeline of approximately

for the full project (with launch in late May / early June 2026). This covers discovery in early 2026, design by spring, development through early summer, and rigorous testing leading into launch. The approach is

(discovery completion, design sign-off, development alpha, content migration, UAT, etc.) to ensure steady progress and stakeholder visibility. Our agile methodology means Chartway’s team will see iterative deliverables (wireframes, prototypes, staging site builds) and can provide feedback throughout – no surprises at the end. This collaborative process reduces risk and ensures the final product aligns perfectly with Chartway’s vision.
Better (“Foundational”) vs. Best (“Enterprise Enhanced”) pricing model

to offer flexibility in investment and feature set. All options will achieve a successful website launch with core functionality, but the tiers allow Chartway to choose the level of depth and long-term scalability:

~4-5 months. A more robust build-out covering most of the site’s content and components. Scalable design system and CMS architecture to support marketing growth (e.g., resource library, campaign pages).
More templates designed, broader migration of existing content, integration of advanced forms/marketing automation, and additional QA cycles for performance tuning.

~6 months. A comprehensive, enterprise-grade solution addressing all of Chartway’s requirements and future-proofing the platform. Includes everything in Better plus multi-region content management (tailoring content for VA, UT, TX within the CMS), multi-language (English/Spanish) out of the box, advanced personalization framework, full content and URL migration, and extended post-launch support. This option lays a
solid digital foundation for the next 5+ years
, enabling Chartway to easily expand features or even add microsites over time.

In summary, Webstacks is excited about the opportunity to partner with Chartway on this initiative.
, Chartway will gain a dedicated team committed to making chartway.com a benchmark example of a modern credit union website – one that is
and easy for your team to manage. We look forward to bringing our expertise to bear and ensuring a successful project that exceeds expectations.
Webstacks will guide Chartway through a comprehensive, phased redesign and migration process, as outlined below. Each phase is iterative and consultative, ensuring value at every step.

phase to align the redesign with Chartway’s goals and constraints. This includes stakeholder workshops (marketing, IT, compliance) to capture objectives and concerns. We’ll perform a content and technical audit of the existing chartway.com, identifying strengths, gaps, and quick wins. Key deliverables are a

, which includes defined user personas, competitive analysis, and a prioritized feature list. A clear project roadmap is established, aligning our efforts with Chartway’s business objectives. Early engagement with Chartway’s compliance and marketing teams ensures legal requirements and brand standards are integrated from day one.
Based on discovery insights, we develop the site’s

and user experience framework. This phase includes building detailed site maps and content models for Chartway’s product lines and member services. We craft wireframes for all major page templates (home, product pages, landing pages, etc.), focusing on intuitive navigation and guided user flows. User personas drive our UX design; for example, a first-time member seeking a loan versus a returning member managing accounts. We ensure content is organized for easy localization (e.g. English/Spanish) and SEO optimization. By involving Chartway’s content and compliance teams in reviews, we ensure that content architecture meets legal, accessibility, and marketing requirements before moving to visual design.
In this phase, Webstacks creates a

that delivers a strong visual identity for Chartway. We translate the new information architecture into high-fidelity mockups, starting with the homepage and key templates (e.g. product pages, landing pages). Our approach is collaborative: we incorporate Chartway’s branding elements (colors, typography, imagery) into “look and feel” explorations, and iterate based on feedback. Simultaneously, we build a reusable design system (pattern library) of components and UI elements (buttons, forms, navigation) to ensure consistency and speed future updates. The result is a cohesive visual language: a bold, trust-building design that can scale across all of Chartway’s digital properties (reflecting regional markets and member segments). We will validate design concepts with sample user testing or feedback sessions, refining the designs to ensure they resonate with Chartway’s audience.

. Based on requirements (security, scalability, multi-site support), we configure the chosen CMS platform and hosting environment. This includes setting up development, staging, and production instances (the RFP noted Rackspace/Linux hosting, but we can migrate to a modern cloud or continue on-premises as needed). We define the CMS architecture: content types for accounts, loans, rates, blog/news, etc., and develop any needed custom modules for forms, calculators, and integrations. Crucially, we plan integrations with key systems: Marketo for marketing automation, banking and loan origination systems (MeridianLink/TCI, Encompass), Q2 digital banking, and others as specified. Our engineers create API integration specifications and prototypes to ensure data flows (e.g. lead capture to Marketo, branch locator queries) work smoothly. By completing this architecture planning before full development, we minimize technical surprises and ensure a secure, scalable platform.

With designs and architecture in hand, we build the front-end of the new website. This involves developing responsive HTML/CSS/JS (or framework) templates for each page type, based on the approved design mockups. We implement the visual design system so that content editors can assemble pages easily. All site functionality is coded, including navigation menus, search, calculators, and interactive elements. During this phase, our team integrates the front-end with the back-end CMS and third-party systems: for example, linking forms and landing pages to Marketo, connecting the site to the branch/ATM locator API, and ensuring single sign-on or social login works as required. We test across devices and browsers continuously to maintain cross-platform quality. Code reviews and automated tests (unit and integration tests) are used to keep quality high. By the end of this phase, the site is feature-complete (with sample content in place) and ready for full content population and testing.

Next, we migrate Chartway’s content into the new site and implement SEO best practices. We develop a migration plan for existing pages and documents, determining what content will be copied, rewritten, or archived. Automated scripts may be used for routine pages; for complex pages, content is manually adjusted to fit new templates. We apply SEO enhancements during migration: setting up metadata controls, adding schema markup for products/offers, and preserving (or improving) URL structure. A list of redirects is implemented to preserve link equity. We also configure analytics and tracking (integrating with tools like Google Analytics, any Chartway dashboards) so that traffic data can flow from day one. The outcome is a fully populated site with search-optimized content that preserves Chartway’s SEO rankings and improves discoverability of key pages.

Quality assurance is integrated throughout, but this phase is a concentrated push to “test everything.” We conduct comprehensive testing: functional testing of all features, cross-browser/device testing for responsive design, and regression testing for integration points. Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA standards) is verified using both automated tools and human evaluation to ensure all member content is accessible. Performance testing is performed (load testing, page speed checks) to confirm the site meets the 90%+ site-health goal. Security testing (penetration testing, OWASP checks) is also done to satisfy Chartway’s requirements. We also review compliance factors (ensuring NCUA/HUD requirements are met, encryption standards, etc. as per the RFP). Any issues found are triaged and fixed iteratively. We provide detailed QA reports and involve Chartway’s team (e.g. compliance officers) to sign off before launch.

Finally, Webstacks manages the production launch and early support. We coordinate the go-live plan: final DNS cutover (whether staying on Rackspace or moving hosts), data freeze and content switchover. Immediately after launch, we monitor site performance and health in real time, ready to fix any urgent issues. During the

period (typically 2–3 weeks post-launch), our team is on-call to resolve bugs and ensure everything is running smoothly. We also deliver training and documentation to Chartway’s content administrators, ensuring they know how to use the new CMS tools (such as scheduling content, adding local rates, or personalizing pages). At handoff, Webstacks provides a final report of work done and a roadmap for any future phases. This structured approach—from discovery through launch—is proven to deliver a successful redesign that meets all strategic goals.

Both options deliver the core requirements (modern responsive design, new CMS, critical integrations, ADA compliance, SEO basics, launch support), while the Enhanced tier provides a broader scope and more robust features. For example, even the Foundational tier includes the essential redesign, CMS, and integrations needed for a successful launch, whereas the Enhanced tier adds enterprise-level capabilities like multi-region content governance, advanced personalization readiness, and a full site migration with no content left behind.
Below is a more detailed breakdown of services by tier
packages meet Chartway’s must-have requirements. Our

. It delivers a balanced solution that aligns with Chartway’s RFP priorities. It directly addresses goals like system integration (Marketo, banking systems), high performance, and compliance, while providing room to grow (for example, adding multi-language later).

The Enhanced tier, while comprehensive, may exceed Chartway’s immediate needs and investment comfort, as it adds extras like premium managed services and additional language support. The Foundational package ensures the site is enterprise-grade (secure, scalable, SEO-optimized), meets Chartway’s current objectives, and provides a strong ROI.

Whichever option you prefer, Chartway gains a high-performing, feature-rich website that can evolve further after launch. Webstacks will remain a partner beyond launch, helping Chartway adjust scope or features (such as adding languages or advanced analytics) as growth needs emerge.

Plan and execute the go-live, targeting a late June launch (well within Q2 2026). We will coordinate deployment to the production environment on

This high-level schedule focuses on essential milestones and follows a sequential (with some parallel) flow. Key check-points (e.g. design approval, integration demos) are built into each phase to keep Chartway’s team aligned with progress.

This timeline aligns with Chartway’s schedule and allows a few weeks of buffer before end of Q2 2026 to accommodate any unforeseen delays. Throughout the project, we will maintain
transparent communication and weekly status updates

to keep everything on track. Should Chartway prefer a phased launch (for example, launching core pages first and rolling out certain sections later), we can accommodate that approach as well – our plan is flexible to adjust as needed.

While not a “Webstacks resource,” it’s worth noting we assume Chartway will designate internal team members for the project: e.g., a project lead on Chartway side to coordinate feedback, Subject Matter Experts for content (marketing team), compliance officers for reviewing regulatory content, and IT contacts for any infrastructure or security reviews. We plan our timeline with the assumption of
and involvement from these stakeholders at key approval points (this is detailed in Assumptions below).
Overall, our resource plan is calibrated to the project scope. The

involve a larger team or extended involvement (e.g. more design iterations, more development complexity, more QA). For example, each tier might involve multiple designers (UX and visual) and additional developers to handle parallel workstreams (like building out personalization features or multiple regional variants).
In terms of investment breakdown, roughly half of the budget will go toward

, with the remainder split among project management, strategy, testing, and content tasks. We will provide a detailed cost breakdown by phase and role in the formal cost proposal (design, development, integrations, etc.). All pricing is in USD and is an estimate based on our current understanding; final pricing would be refined with Chartway upon confirming scope details. We are flexible in structuring the engagement commercially (milestone-based payments or a monthly schedule) per Chartway’s preference.
To ensure the project’s success, we have made a number of assumptions in our plan. These key assumptions should be validated and agreed upon by both Webstacks and Chartway:

Chartway will provide access to necessary stakeholders and SMEs (Marketing, IT, Compliance, etc.) for discovery workshops, feedback sessions, and content approvals in a timely manner. We assume swift turnaround on reviews (e.g. design sign-off, content approval) to keep the timeline on track.
Existing website content (copy, images, documents) will be made available for migration. We assume Chartway will supply any

content or copy changes needed for the redesign (with our team assisting in content migration and minor copy editing, but not full content writing services unless scoped). Any major content rewrites or additional content creation (e.g., new blog articles, new imagery) are assumed to be handled by Chartway or can be added as an extra service.

Chartway will provide brand guidelines, logos, imagery, and any existing design assets to ensure the redesign aligns with your brand. If a brand refresh is happening in parallel, we assume those new brand assets (fonts, color palettes, etc.) will be provided at project start.

We assume that necessary third-party platforms (Marketo, online banking system, MeridianLink/TCI, Encompass mortgage app, Q2 digital banking, etc. as noted in the RFP) will have accessible APIs or embed options that we can utilize. Any licensing or fees for third-party software (e.g., if a new search engine tool or translation plugin is needed) are assumed to be covered by Chartway. We will work with Chartway’s vendors as needed during integration (e.g., coordinating with your online banking provider for SSO integration).

The new site will be hosted on a modern hosting platform (we recommend Vercel). We assume no legacy server constraints. DNS access will be provided for go-live. We’ll implement all reasonable security measures (per RFP requirements like SOC 2, TLS 1.2+, DDoS mitigation) on the new hosting environment, but we assume Chartway’s IT/security team will be involved in reviewing and approving the hosting approach. Any security reviews or penetration testing by Chartway can be accommodated if scheduled.

We assume Chartway’s team is available to attend training sessions and that they have basic technical proficiency to manage content with the new CMS after training. We will provide documentation, but assume ongoing content editing after launch will be handled by Chartway’s internal marketing/web team (unless a separate retainer with Webstacks is established).

Any specific compliance requirements (e.g. disclosures, Equal Housing logos, NCUA/FDIC statements, GDPR if applicable) will be communicated to us. We will build the site to be ADA/WCAG 2.1 AA compliant and assume Chartway will perform any required compliance audits (or we can assist with a third-party audit as an added service). We assume compliance reviews (e.g. by legal or regulators) will happen during UAT and any required changes will be within the scope of the project as long as they align with best practices (extensive compliance changes beyond standard might need change orders).

Our default assumption is to support the last 2 versions of major browsers (Chrome, Edge, Safari, Firefox) and typical modern devices. If Chartway has members using older technology (for example, older versions of IE or very old mobile devices), those can be discussed, but our plan assumes modern browser support consistent with a forward-looking, secure site.

The scope outlined (number of templates, features, integrations, content volume) is based on current knowledge (including the provided URL list and RFP requirements). We assume no significant new sections or major features will be added beyond this scope without re-scoping. If new needs emerge (e.g., “let’s add an authenticated member portal” or “we want to build a custom web app feature”), that would be handled via change control and could impact timeline/cost.
The timeline is based on project kickoff by

(or earlier if possible, post-proposal approval in Dec 2025) and assumes continuous progress. Delays in approvals, content delivery, or unexpected changes could shift the timeline. We assume alignment on timeline and that both teams will work proactively to meet the Q2 2026 launch goal.

We assume the existing site’s SEO equity (rankings, backlinks) is important to maintain. Our plan for redirects and URL structure is based on current URLs from the crawl report (Chartway URL list). We assume we can map old URLs to new ones in a straightforward way (some URL structure improvements will be made, but we will not leave important pages without a redirect). Any pages that Chartway decides to drop or consolidate will be identified so we can redirect accordingly.

We assume Chartway will actively participate in user acceptance testing and sign off on the site before launch. Launch will be scheduled at a time agreeable to both parties, likely during a low-traffic period or maintenance window, to minimize member disruption.

Our proposal includes up to 90 days of post-launch support. This assumes normal support activities (bug fixes, minor tweaks, answering questions). Significant new features or large scope changes after launch are not included in this support window (they can be handled in a Phase 2 or support retainer). We assume an ongoing maintenance arrangement can be discussed as needed after the included support period.
Validating these assumptions early will help mitigate risks and ensure a smooth project. We welcome any questions or clarifications on these points.
Every complex project carries some risks. We have identified key potential risks for the Chartway redesign and our plans to mitigate each:
Delays in approvals, content readiness, or unexpected technical hurdles could threaten the Q2 2026 launch date.

with frequent check-ins. The timeline includes buffer time especially in the later stages to absorb minor delays. We will set intermediate milestones (design sign-off, content freeze dates, etc.) and closely monitor progress. If any delays occur, the PM will immediately communicate impacts and we’ll collaborate with Chartway to realign priorities (e.g., we could prioritize launch of critical pages first, with less critical features in a phase 2, if absolutely necessary). Our weekly status meetings will ensure any blockers are addressed quickly.
With a large volume of content to migrate, there is a risk of content being missing, formatted incorrectly, or broken links/redirects affecting SEO.
early (using the URL list provided) to identify all pages to bring over. A detailed

spreadsheet will be prepared and reviewed to ensure every legacy URL has a destination. We will also execute content migration in a staging environment where Chartway staff can review and sign off on each section’s content. Automated tools and scripts will be used where possible to reduce manual error, and our QA will include link checking and content verification. Post-launch, we’ll monitor analytics and Google Search Console for any 404 errors or traffic drops and fix promptly.
New feature requests or expanded requirements could inflate scope, causing budget or timeline overruns.

in a Statement of Work, based on this proposal.
